===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|abductiō||robbing; abduction}}, from {{m|la|abdūcō||take or lead away}}, from {{term|ab||away|lang=la}} + {{m|la|dūcō||to lead}}<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=2}}</ref>.
* {{sense|physiology}} From {{etyl|fr|en}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|abductus|lang=la}}.
* Compare French {{term|lang=fr|abduction}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/əbˈdʌk.ʃn̩/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æbˈdʌk.ʃn̩/|/æbˈdək.ʃn̩/|/əbˈdək.ʃn̩/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# Leading away; a [[carry]]ing away. {{defdate|Early 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=3}}</ref>
# {{context|physiology|lang=en}} The act of [[abduce|abducing]] or [[abduct]]ing; a [[draw]]ing apart; the [[movement]] which [[separate]]s a [[limb]] or other part from the [[axis]], or middle line, of the body. {{defdate|Mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>{{rfex}}
# {{context|logic|lang=en}} A [[syllogism]] or form of [[argument]] in which the [[major]] premise is [[evident]], but the minor is only [[probable]]. {{defdate|Late 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* '''2005''', Ronnie Cann, Ruth Kempson, Lutz Marten, ''The Dynamics of Language, an Introduction'', page 256:
#*: The significance of such a step is that it is not morphologically triggered: it is a step of '''abduction''', and what is required here is a meta-level process of reasoning.
# The [[wrongful]], and usually [[forcible]], [[carry off|carrying off]] of a human being. {{defdate|Mid 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''the '''abduction''' of a child''

